Today, the Ukrainian Parliament, in the course of the amendments to the Criminal Procedure Code, rejected an attempt to repeal the article condemning the leader of the opposition, Yulia Timoshenko.
An amendment that would lead to the release of the former Prime Minister in prison was rejected during the second reading of the draft law on the commutation of sentences for economic offences.
In October, Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for signing a gas deal with Russia, which was found to be unprofitable.
The sentence is not yet final; the court will hear Timoshenko's appeal in December.
Timoshenko claims that the sentence is a political revenge of the regime; in the West, the trial was also suspected of bias.
A proposal to repeal article 365 of the Criminal Procedure Code, under which the former Prime Minister had been convicted, had been supported by 147 members of Parliament.
Ratification would require 226 votes.
