Feeding of children suffering from obesity: No breakfast and sausage for dinner
More than one third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 weigh more than the norm; while 9 per cent of schoolchildren are overweight, 5 per cent suffer from obesity.
According to the latest study, children suffering from obesity usually come from unhealthy families.
Once again, we see the importance of the environment and the behaviours that accompany the human being for his or her healthy development.
For example, sausage appears almost twice as often as in families with normal weight children.
More than 19% of children suffering from obesity ate fries for dinner on the eve of a survey on an educational event called Obesity is not an accident.
Moreover, the families of children suffering from obesity do not engage in sports, but most of the families of modern-day schoolchildren - only 15 per cent of the children said that their parents took at least once a week to engage in sports.
The study was conducted among 900 children.
The study was conducted at the end of the last school year and involved nearly 900 primary school students throughout Bohemia.
Obesity was not an accident for the second year in a row, with the support of Všeobecná zdravotní pojšøvna and Unilever.
To date, more than 12,000 pupils in grades 4 to 8 have joined the project.
Good nutrition and sufficient sports effort are the main determinants of the rapidly growing number of children who suffer from either excessive weight or obesity.
"For example, only half of the respondents said that they eat five meals a day, according to the breakfast-food-food-supper-supper scheme, which is one of the best nutritional conditions," says one of the findings of the study.
No lunch and sausage at night.
Experts warn that even relative details such as regular family breakfasttime are important for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23 per cent of schoolchildren ' s families eat breakfast together.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast separately.
The worst revelation is that in every ten families, people don't eat breakfast at all.
And yet breakfast is the basis of the right daily diet.
The study found that roasted food is more commonly used in families with children suffering from obesity.
Almost everyone, regardless of weight, drinks sweet cool drinks every day (70%).
Although more than 40 per cent of children regularly engage in sports, this figure is more than halved to 15 per cent when it comes to their parents.
Make your own menu.
In another part of the study, selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) were asked to draw up their own menu based on the products offered and based on their tastes and preferences.
"The food preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15 are far from ideal with regard to healthy nutrition."
Their favorite food includes a large number of flour, meat, and sweet meals.
"A particular concern is the high popularity of sweet cool drinks," says the final part of the study.
As the main dinner meal, the pasta defeated a bird with a small weight.
However, children showed little interest in beans, fish, and vegetables.
Desiring a Healthy Lifestyle
The study also showed that children were willing to change their eating habits, provided that they were provided with relevant information.
"A large number of participants in the survey team showed a significant shift in preferences towards healthy food when they filled out the questionnaire after completing the lecture Obesity is not an accident," the outcome of the project.
This was particularly evident, for example, in the case of sweet cool drinks, more children began to prefer them to water.
In addition, children more often marked birds and fish as the main meal, limiting the number of sweet meals and pastries.
