V Need for Speed: Escape occurs in America.
Overview
What was supposed to be a carefree walk turned into a routine morning trip to work due to a series of totally inappropriate and careless mistakes.
The ambition was met to a certain extent, but it doesn't matter, because no one clearly wanted to do the extra work.
Before the release of the new version, there were great hopes with the subheading "The Escape".
It was expected to move the previous series of "Need For Speed" in a new direction; the demonstration versions showed that the game would take its rightful place in the racing game genre.
We were curious to see the parts of the game where the main hero comes out of the car and runs.
As often happens with NFS, there's a lot different in the end from what we expected.
The game is a pretty good arcade race, but the general impression is that there are a few unnecessary mistakes that have been in this series for several years.
So it's not really a mistake, it's an unexplained laziness of developers.
The adventure begins very well.
You're becoming part of a story whose main hero, Jack, decides to solve some personal problems by participating in an illegal race through America.
You get in a car on the west coast in San Francisco, and your job is to get to New York first.
This idea has a few interesting features.
The route consists of ten stages divided into more than fifty races.
This means that each race runs along its own route, and the individual stages take place in a diverse and interesting environment.
So it doesn't feel like the game is always the same.
Although the graphs are at the same level as in the previous parts of the series, it is nice to see some of the tracks.
Still, the game does not cause strong emotions.
While driving through the desert, it is pleasant to drive in the autumn suburbs or high in snowy mountains.
Besides, racing sometimes revives an unusual detail.
For example, in the desert, you are caught in a sandstorm that significantly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, the mountains need to be careful not to fall under the avalanche.
Individual races are rather well organized.
There are only a few varieties, but that's enough.
For a while you're trying to outrun a few rivals (in fact a normal race); then you're trying to improve time (standard race with a second) or you're competing with one opponent.
Among other things, you run into the police from time to time, which makes your task even more difficult.
The components outside the car are new.
It's just an interactive animation where most of the time Jack runs away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right time.
It's no big deal.
Although it is surprising that these fragments are much smaller than you would have expected (only three to be precise).
In fact, it turns out that it's a good thing to play because it doesn't bother; given all the above, it's one of the things that makes the game more entertaining.
The racing model follows previous models.
It means that it is no longer something special, but it cannot be considered a weakness.
If you're looking for a real-life simulation, you're gonna have to look elsewhere.
Yet this model of driving is very suitable for dynamic races, although better options can be found in the market.
So far, so good.
After a while, however, problems begin.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model isn't so good.
You don't expect a game like this to be a complicated transformation or a collision, but if you have no idea before you hit an object, how your car will behave, something's wrong.
Usually, by passing or passing cars in a dense stream, you sometimes touch a slightly different car, and yet sometimes in a similar situation, your car starts to freak out.
Or she broke up.
It's not important because of the restart system, but it's enough to ruin the fun.
Restarts are designed so that if you break or get away from the track, the game takes you back to the point where it stopped.
However, only five restarts are available for each race.
If you use them all, you're gonna have to start the race from the start.
It's useful in case something doesn't work out, but you can't rely entirely on it.
Sometimes restarts aren't enough, and you have to learn by heart a separate part of the race.
An important disadvantage of the game is the fact that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some turns have to be done in a certain way, or you're just not gonna fit in.
In other cases, you meet civilian cars in a certain location in the same configuration, regardless of whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is particularly annoying in situations where you see your rival travel easily between two cars moving in the opposite direction, whereas when you're in there, the cars are already positioned so that you either have to pass them or lose speed.
It doesn't matter when you get close to them; it's arranged that the situation always happens in front of your nose.
The rivals have other advantages.
During the game, you find several places where, regardless of the time, the same rival overtakes you in the same place.
It's especially obvious at the end of the game, on a long bridge where you're going in the opposite direction.
Obviously, your opponent must stand before you no matter what.
The thing is, when he goes in front of you, he makes you look worse, which leads to one or more accidents in this area.
You can understand the attempt to make the game more interesting and filled with adrenaline, but it's so obvious that it's quickly getting annoying.
Too bad, because despite a simple model of driving, the game is interesting and sometimes so full of events that you don't have time to pay attention to what's happening around you.
It doesn't matter what keeps you bored-- a concept with fifty unique paths, a sequence of races or something.
The idea of changing cars during a race is unusual.
You need to track gas stations along the way, because that's where your car can change, even though in most cases the one you already have is enough.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports machines are suitable for cities; powerful American cars are for straight sections of the highway; and exotic super-sport cars for technical driving, for example on curved mountain routes.
===Story mode===Story mode is closely linked to Hallenge mode; it is a race by individual sites that you will learn as the game progresses.
Here, you win both medals and points common to Hallenges and story regimes for your personal business.
Many opportunities are available for higher driving levels, ranging from cars to profile data.
In addition, the profile is linked to the Autolog online function, which, among other things, compares your performance with that of other players, and provides communication with the public.
Here's another flaw that's hard to understand; it's an example from the last race in sequence.
You and your car will enter the subway tunnel (to be assumed) where you run down the rails in the dark (to be assumed to be so).
Your speedometer shows the numbers between 150 and 200 km/h (to be assumed) when a subway train suddenly hits you in the back, turning your car into a pile of scrap metal.
For a few days, our revision discussed whether, at the time of the game's creation, no one really thought for a second, or whether its creators really thought we were such idiots.
The technical content of the game is nothing special; but the overall impression from the video series is mostly pleasant, sometimes even amazing.
Although it is a pity that in some critical moments, the quality of the recording has sometimes declined quite significantly.
This is especially true of incidents involving a large number of participants, where a good recording wouldn't help you much either.
Sound's fine; soundtrack's for an amateur.
To please the widest possible youth audience, soundtracks of different styles have entered the soundtrack; but it is unlikely that many people will buy the game because of her music.
The general impression of Need for Speed is that the escape is quite random.
If the game avoided obviously unnecessary mistakes, we could honestly say that Escape is the best part of NFS in the last few years.
Anyway, the game leaves a sense of incompleteness.
Of course, it's good fun, but prepare to see the flaws blind you like a searchlight at the airport.
