Brand history:
IBM innovators enter the second century of their existence.
If someone wants to find a word that IMB's most likely to express, the closest one is likely to be "long-lived."
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution; the company is considered very modern, although it was founded over a hundred years ago.
The firm's long-term worth was laid down by its first boss, the dreamer Thomas J. Watson the Senior.
He believed in his motto that many of the world's problems could easily be solved if people wanted to think.
His slogan, "Think!", became the stamp surrounding the life of the future giant (and also the name of his internal magazine, which IMB began publishing in 1935).
Moreover, it was the foundation of a corporate culture that Watson carefully built.
"For us in IBM, long-term thinking means constant movement towards the future.
IBM survived and prospered for a hundred years because she remained faithful to her original values, although she was not afraid to change everything around her.
In our first hundred years, it allowed us to transform technology, business, and company.
In the second century, we hope to achieve even more," says the current head of Samuel J. Palmizano's company on the occasion of the anniversary.
Complex system
In the 1930s, Watson approached the issue of employee care in the same way that Batya in the Czech Republic - IMB employees were among the first American employees to have paid leave, employer insurance, elegant uniforms, and a complex system of bonuses for the best inventors and entrepreneurs.
The long-term relationship between IBM and consumers is equally advanced.
From the beginning, the company had a brilliant use for talented people, one of the world's first companies to eliminate all the discrimination that gave it an excellent choice.
Concurs with the anti-discrimination strategy and the current plan that a woman, Virginia Rometti, will replace Palmizano next year.
She worked at IBM for 30 years; she is now director of sales, marketing and development.
Over the past few years, IBM has organized meetings, online brainstorms, which have generated many future innovations.
No wonder there's a lot of ideas-- about half a million people working in the company.
An organization with a good reputation
The firm ' s strong position in business is supported by strong internal and external image.
