IBM history: from cheese knife to space flight.
==History==IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York City a hundred years ago and its original title, "Corporation, tabulation, recording" was rather complex.
It took the name IBM in 1924, originally called the brand used for the company's branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation of the future IBM was the merger of four companies, which began in the 1880s.
They owned technology such as the legendary "stable clock", i.e., a clock that records the time when employees come and leave their jobs.
The architect of the new company was the businessman Charles Ranlet Flint, who until 1930 also headed the company's board of trustees.
Flint hired a rival company director, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The leader then pushed the founder of IBM into the shadow of Watson's ideas, which remain the basis of a permanent corporate culture and identity.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as is clear from the name, began with the production and sale of various business equipment, ranging from cheese knives and cutters to cashiers.
In the first four years of Watson's leadership, revenues doubled to $9 million, and a massive expansion of the company to all continents began.
Watson became so important to the company that almost 40 years later his son, Thomas Watson Jr., took his place in the director's chair.
Under his leadership, IBM began to develop artificial intelligence technologies and created the first programming language.
In the 1960s, both employees and IBM computers helped NASA control space flights to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969, a man flew to the Moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first computer family, the IBM Line System/360.
The classic PC, which defined the computer standards of that time, called IBM 5150, appeared on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold computers to the Chinese company Lenovo, while buying a consulting office called PricewaterhouseCoopers, thus focusing entirely on consulting and high-value-added services.
Over the past three years, IBM has made great strides with its Smarter Planet concept.
Its purpose is to make reasonable use of technologies in areas that have not yet been planned and to improve road and urban management.
In commerce, IBM recently introduced the Smarter Commerce platform, which helps businessmen control the entire trade cycle.
IBM traditions are strong even in our country.
In the former Czechoslovakia, as the first country in central and eastern Europe, IBM founded its branch in 1932.
Today, IBM CZ also runs a strategic outsourcing centre in Brno.
The headquarters of central and eastern Europe is located in Prague, where there is also a world-level research group dedicated to speech recognition.
