Trends in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five state-owned tourism agencies could work in the former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Because travel to the West was severely restricted, travel agencies at that time largely sold tours to the socialist bloc.
Thus, Czech tourists travelled to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West, which led to significant restrictions on Czech tourists travelling to Yugoslavia.
A great paradox of the socialist period was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed to travel individually in socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to go on his own, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter of invitation from that country was needed; another individual journey was impossible.
At the time, travel agencies offered to travel to the West, but either you had to stand in line all night with a sleeping bag or you had "good friends" at the agency.
And that wasn't all.
Foreign exchange permits were required for travel to the West, and were not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; without a foreign exchange permit, it was not possible to obtain money (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
The Czechs spent most of their vacations at home, which resulted in a large number of cottages and summer houses, a habit that continues to this day.
Since 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic has thus survived a real revolution.
While until 1989 the GDR or Bulgaria holiday was the culmination of our travels, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations in countries around the world.
The great paradox, which we no longer realize, is that until 1989 we could not freely visit the most popular Croatia today, as it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
At the beginning of 1990, the need for a visa to neighbouring countries of Western Europe was abolished, marking the beginning of a huge wave of short trips, mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovakians couldn't afford to go to the West, and everyone wanted to go there for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in the parks in tents because their income at the time was insufficient for a hotel or board.
A typical feature of Czech tourism at that time was the desire to bring your own food (conserves, salami, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a freely convertible Czech crown, and after decades our tourists can finally freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living and average income grew, which led to another important circumstance around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has enabled travel agencies to prepare regular flights carried out by chartered airlines; compared to the past, flights have now become incredibly cheap owing to the possibility of ordering wholesale discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs didn't need a visa to visit almost every developed world except the US, which made our journeys even easier.
The next significant event in the history of travel after the revolution took place in 2000, with great demand leading to the historic first direct charter from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have taken Czech tourists to warm exotic countries, and this winter flights from the Czech Republic will take place in 12 exotic directions.
At present, about 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another important development of this period, which symbolizes our development after the revolution, took place in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States abolished the need to obtain a visa for Czech tourists, and our country has thus permanently joined the world's most developed countries.
For the first time in history in 2008, Czechs spent more than half of their leave abroad (50.3%); and for the first time in history, they spent more than 15,000 kroner per person during leave abroad, including their expenses at their destination.
