The Austrian pavilion, designed by Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 World Exhibition in Brussels, is a well-known example of a modern post-war architecture with its simple forms, glass halls, bold enough to express faith in technological progress.
Swanzer's pavilion won the Grand Prix by architecture in 1958 for its lightly floating steel and glass structure.
