He eventually became famous for the world in 1973 with his legendary four-cylinder tower, BMW, and her sister, a cup-shaped building.
The pavilion, conceived as a temporary exhibition building, was moved to the Swiss Garden near the Southern Station of Vienna, transformed and opened as the Museum of the 20th Century in 1962 - and is often referred to as the House of the 20th Century for this reason.
In any case, the building was not suitable for the museum for technical and spatial reasons - there were no walls on which art could be hung and poor air conditioning.
However, it continued to be used until modern art in Vienna was given a new home.
The house has been empty since 2001, and its condition has been getting worse and worse.
Architect Adolf Krishanitz has now restored a pavilion called House of the 21st Century to be used as a museum of modern art.
