Peter Engleund's intense and very kind new book, "Beauty and Grievance: The Personal History of World War I", begins with a long list of actors whose heart is dying.
Here's a suggestion: carefully cut out this page and use it as a bookmark.
You'll get to know these people very close as Mr. Engleund tells you, and this list of actors will be your GPS, your beacon, at times when, like one of these men and women, you'll get lost on the road and be lost in the fog of war.
Mr. Engleund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new Permanent Secretary of the Swedish Academy, who awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book he's written now is unusual, he describes it, quite precisely, as "an anti-history job."
It has few known names, important treaties or famous battles; there are few ambassadors, clever journalists, or discussions on tactics and military equipment.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, but a book about what it looked like.
The book "Beauty and sorrow" brought together the experiences of 20 more or less invisible men and women from both sides of the front line, from schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and employees.
Some of these people are gonna be heroes.
Someone gets captured, loses his arm or leg, goes crazy or dies.
Their lives are shimmering like church candles: new ones are added to many others, and some are lost at that time.
Mr. Engleund's book is a departure from the standard of historical books.
This is an amendment to the notion that World War I was only a severe trench war on the West Front.
"Beauty and sorrow" ably provides a panorama of other theatres of war: Alps, Balkans, Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
The soldiers in this book fall bee hives; one of them meets Christmas in Egypt under pyramids; the unresolved problem is tsetse flies.
