The walls have eyes: How researchers study you on Facebook
Before becoming a new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Bering Bravik was an ordinary guy who put his anti-immigration views on the Internet.
On Monday, Bravik, who had confessed to the massacre in Norway in July, which claimed the lives of 77 people, appeared at his first public hearing.
Although Bravik could act alone, he was far from being alone online: he spent a lot of time preparing to attack his computer, communicating with millions of nationalists who support the right groups on social media.
After the summer tragedy, researchers wanted to learn more about these people.
But how do we find them?
Easy. All you have to do is go on Facebook.
"We realized it was easy to get to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recently published report on the European cyberpolysis of the British research centre DEMOS.
The personal data on Facebook is so large, says Bartlett, that researchers could easily use the website's promotional tool to single out the necessary demographic group with scientific accuracy - what market scientists have been doing for several years.
Bartlett's team discovered half a million right-wing fans across Europe and then put them in advertising, but instead of showing a new group or diet, the ad offered to the user a survey that asked about their level of education, attitudes to violence and optimism about their own future.
With the help of Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 participants in 14 extreme right-wing parties in 11 European countries without even leaving the office.
"It's a whole new way to do research," says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not as striking: online right-wing people - most often young males, disgruntled by immigration.
But suddenly, "those who combine their online activity with offline activity are smarter, more democratic and less aggressive than those who are hiding behind the monitor."
The work of DEMOS is only one example of how Facebook becomes a new popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centres, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything, from health issues to social trends, which are expressed in Lake, posts on the wall, and status updates.
With over 800 million active users adding an average of three notes a day, Facebook's "super-relevant information" triggers a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with the site's title in the title by 800 per cent over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it provides an opportunity to study people who cannot be reached on the street with a notebook.
"In the early days, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to join the party and they'd never accept you," Bartlett says.
"Facebook rules out all of this - you're talking to them directly."
Others say that the site could identify and investigate social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of Wisconsin University, Madison, and her colleagues, showed that students who discussed their drunken Facebook activities were much more at risk of alcoholism than students who were silent about it.
Moreno suggests that students' peers, such as their hostel mentors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who too often renews drunken status.
"You can't solve the problem without identifying it," reported Washington Post Dimitri Christakis, co-author Moreno and director of the Children's Health, Behaviour and Development Centre at the Seattle Children's Research Institute.
"We found a way to identify at-risk children we wouldn't otherwise find."
Facebook also constantly extracts various kinds of data about its users.
The website ' s Data Processing Unit processed statistics on the status of relations and Valentine ' s Day, the mid-term voter turnout in 2010, and the National Happiness Index (mainly using information only available to them - Cyber Freedom Champions have long insisted that the site should make its extensive data collection publicly available for research).
But Facebook users know that the website watches them whether they like it or not - in exchange for playing Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away from you, the site can process your personal data.
But what happens when Facebook users get involved in a study they don't even know about?
While researchers have strict standards for offline research, online data are publicly available.
"I don't think many users at least thought that a researcher could observe their profiles," says Neil Selwin, a socialologist from the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a study he had conducted in 2006 using publicly available Facebook student pages.
"As far as they could imagine, it was just between them and their friends."
Then the question of methodology arises.
Even offline, there's no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
It's impossible to know on Facebook how much information is in the profile and on the user's page.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do outside Facebook are two completely different things," Selwin says.
That is why, despite years of work in technology research, Selwin thinks that the notebook and pen are still the best research tools available.
"Nothing can replace going into the real world and communicating with real people," he says.
"Social research is supposed to be about social research, and most social research is still offline."
