7 lessons from Steve Jobs' lost interview at the theater this week.
After Steve Jobs' death on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, describing the technical genius as the Great Inventor of Modernity.
But what Apple fans can think of as the biggest discovery in a recently discovered interview that was remembered in the run-up to the pre-emerging major markets this week is how much this creative mind understood in business processes and manufacturing technologies.
He was, of course, a designer, a dreamer, and he thought he was a hippie, but he was also a thorough organizer and a process master who believed that many business managers suffered from "the pain of thinking that a really great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] a great idea from a great product separates a huge amount of skilled work."
Back in 1995, Bob Kringley created the Triumph Nerd Television series about the appearance of a personal computer, and he spent more than an hour with Jobs for a unique long conversation.
By that time, about 10 years had passed since Jobs was kicked out of Apple, and he was already working for his new computer company, NeXT, in anticipation of massive Internet development.
While a small part of Kringley's interview was used in Nerds, he says the original interviews went missing during transport.
It was only after Jobs' death that a full VHS was found in the director's garage.
This footage, slightly edited, was the basis for Steve Jobs' 68-minute film: The Lost Interview, which is released on Landmark Theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For a man known for his hatred of detailed interviews, Jobs seems unusual here to present his technological philosophy and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
In four different points during the interview, there are long intervals between questions and answers - reflections on 10 to 15 seconds, where Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts to be more precise.
