The Court will approve the digital television transition in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme Court (SC) rejected the constitutional claims put forward by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the Presidential Decree, which moved the so-called digital television transition from 2021 to 2015, as there were no eight votes required to cancel it.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Mesa, considered that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his authority by issuing a decree detailing the actions to move to digital ground television.
As a result, the constitutional claims submitted by the Senate were rejected because there was no qualified majority of the eight votes required for the court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree and it remains in force.
The draft statement prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero proposed that the decree should be declared unconstitutional, because the regulation of the radio and television programme was a right established by law for the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and the legislative reserve.
Only Salvidar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margaret Luna and Sanchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
On this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional debates to refute the decree and to support the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions referred to therein concerning the introduction of digital broadcasting.
At the ministerial meeting, it was also decided to reject the request of the Chamber of Deputies without entering into a discussion of the draft, also under the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he disagreed with the arguments of the draft in the sense that the federal executive could not determine the general rules for the measures to be prepared by the public administration.
"I also do not believe that, if this had happened, it would have affected the autonomy of the regulatory body," and recalled that the planning of public policy in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is related to the federal executive branch, which has a constitutional mandate, the administration of the State.
The replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years, has led to better use of the radio-electric spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponement of the transition, he said, would mean deferring the benefits of transformation into digital form, which included meeting public needs, which had more than a technical dimension, "because it covered economic, social, political and national security issues".
These questions, he said, "requires the whole system of public economic governance, includes a group of authorities which the Constitution unites into the public executive".
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world had already completed digital broadcasting, and he had done so through the executive, despite the existence of highly specialized technical institutions.
It cannot be concluded that the Government, in adopting the decree under discussion, which in any case affects the competence of Congress, ensures administrative compliance with the laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly, he said.
In Michoacán, the possibility of counting "voting by voice" is being analysed.
According to the PPR, the difference between first and second seats in the Governor ' s elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting 879 votes out of a total of 6.074.
The possibility of counting "voting by vote" is real with regard to this year's electoral process in Michoacán, where the difference between the first and second seats in the Governor's elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting 879 votes out of a total of 6.074.
In the light of this, the President of the General Council of the Michoacan Institute for Elections (IMI), Maria de Los Angeles Lianderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the electorate had adopted a set of principles to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
It should be recalled that Michoacán did not adopt the Constitution or the State Electoral Code or the Electoral Law Act, since the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for their entry into force in the electoral process, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel did not include its publication within the time frame set out in the law in the State Official Gazette, stating that he had some objections.
On the same day, 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice (JJJJJ) ruled on a constitutional claim submitted by the local legislature and called the State representative's vote on constitutional reform "unenforceable and illegal" because he did not have the right to "permit or support them".
In an interview on the possibility of "voting by voice", Maria de los Ángueles Lianderal argued that with the adoption of suitable principles by the General Council of IBM, it would be possible to present a partial or total counting of votes by the local electoral body.
For example, a partial recalculation of one or more ballot boxes may be made on the condition that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of the ballot and counting of documents in the urn or he is not in the Chair ' s custody; or there are obvious errors or corrections to the record.
Moreover, there may be a general recalculation of votes in all ballot boxes when there is evidence that the difference between the alleged winner of the election in question and those who won the second ballot is less than or equal to 1 per cent, provided that at the beginning of the session there is a request from the party and/or coalition that nominated the second candidate.
The total counting of votes will also take place if, at the end of the normal counting, it is established that the difference between the winner and the candidate for the second seat is less than or equal to 1 per cent, provided that there is a request from the political party whose candidate is second in the case of the exclusion of the ballot boxes which have been recorded in the partial recalculation.
It is worth noting that there are elections in Morelia, where, according to the EDP, the difference between the first and second seats is only 0.16%, not even 129 votes out of a total of 923 minutes.
