A new Italian Government will be formed on Wednesday
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monty, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face the crisis that has brought this country to the brink of an economic disaster.
The appointed Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monty, will meet on Wednesday with the President of Italy to present a new government that will face a crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic disaster and damaged the entire eurozone.
A statement from the Presidential Palace stated that Monty, appointed on Sunday, would meet on Wednesday with the President, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he could form a government.
He was expected to present a cabinet composed mainly of technocrats, although it was not clear when the new executive body would take office.
Monty said that he would present to the President the results of his talks with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to reaffirm my full confidence in our country's ability to emerge from this difficult period," said the former European Commissioner to reporters.
Monty did not say explicitly that he was able to form a government, but the tone of his comments showed that the obstacles had been overcome.
"The structure is well defined now," he said.
Monty completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, which is much less than usual, because Italy was struggling with a political and financial crisis that brought their debt to a critical level.
The Administration, under the leadership of former European Commissioner Monty, must approve the austerity package required by European leaders to restore confidence in Italy.
Based on the pressure on Monty to hurry, unstable markets set the income from Italy's BTP bonds at over 7% for 10 years, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to be rescued.
Emma Marchaglia, the leader of the Italian Federation of Employers, told reporters after a meeting with Monty, "We said we would actively support this government."
We believe that this Government is Italy ' s last chance to emerge from this critical situation.
Monty's chances of success were largely based on the support of the LDP party Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday because of the crisis.
"We believe Professor Monty's efforts should lead to a good outcome," said reporters Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centrist-right party.
The support of the LDP, the largest party in Italy, is important because so far many of its members have opposed the government majority of technocrats that form Monty.
Parliamentary support
The new Monty Government must have strong parliamentary support for reforms that are likely to be not popular reforms of austerity.
Any blocking or suspension of these attempts could lead to a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks increased pressure to warn that Monty's failure could be a disaster.
Monty began consultations on Monday with political parties, alliances and business groups, as well as youth and women ' s organizations.
He's gonna finish his meetings on Tuesday night.
Monty was appointed on Sunday of Napolitano, who allowed an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief break at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italy's debt now reached a critical level, against the backdrop of uncertainty as to whether the new Prime Minister would succeed.
Saving Italy with a public debt of 1.8 billion euros would be too much for the eurozone's modern financial defenders.
Monty said that his Government would be in place until the next elections scheduled for 2013, despite popular forecasts that politicians would only allow him time to undertake reforms before the new elections were scheduled.
Monty said that he would like to include politicians in his office, but the major parties insist that he should be made up of only technical specialists, demonstrating their dissatisfaction with the financial situation affecting the process.
Political sources reported that mutual mistrust and opposition by the parties made the attempt to include political figures more difficult.
