UNAM asphalt can avoid cracks
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Chemical Faculty, developed a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture of the best environmental and temperature-resistant quality.
If the road surface signals were to be addressed, it would be necessary to repair some 200,000 pits in each rainy season in the capital area of Mexico City, says Rafael Herrera Nahera, a researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemicals, and adds that if the construction and maintenance of the paved road surface are correct, the number of pits can be reduced or reduced to zero.
His lecture on the technological view of pits, read in the context of the International Year of Chemistry, reported that the laboratory for which he was responsible was developing a polymer-modified bitumen for the production of a mixture with the characteristics close to the bitumen, but with the best resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nahera said that this type of modified bitumen could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, as in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and thus to resist the formation of pits.
He explained that the bitumen, the hardest part of oil, was a sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some of them a high molecular mass called asphaltens, and others a low molecular mass called maltens, which together gave road cover to its characteristic viscous behavior.
The viscosity behavior of the bitumen is the fact that he behaves like a liquid in high Tepmeratures of about 180 degrees, with 120 degrees of viscosity very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius, he keeps his condition almost firm, while at very low temperatures the bitumen becomes fragile, he said.
This means that resistance to street asphalt is not permanent, but changes during the day, depending on natural conditions and temperature, the chemical engineer said.
The scientist noted that the streets of Mexico City were mostly covered with a flexible cover composed of six layers of material, the last three of which included bitumen.
Among the uppermost layers is a bitumen made of small stones dropped into the bitumen and then pressed.
Every stone that makes this coating, he said, is trapped in a bitumen.
When vehicles are driven and effort is exerted, this helps the forces to be very well distributed across the road surface.
If it were a modified asphalt, they would have been even better distributed, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt surface, he added, the last layer, which is called a layer of wear, which is made of a small stone, which is actually sand, also loaded into asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will be in contact with the wheels of transport, it must have more resistance than asphalt coating and provide friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and disseminate these forces, the wear layer also requires adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature variations, were also very important factors for consideration, especially water, he said, because it had a significant impact on asphalt.
When the land is raw, the water enters the surface and it is difficult to get out of it, it causes all layers of the surface to soften and therefore the pits to form.
When the pits are formed, he said, the first wear-on layer is worn out and only then it affects the bitumen, but the damage does not occur instantaneously, which should be addressed in the first signs of the maintenance programmes.
Also, a member of the National Research System explained that the transport load was another important factor in creating holes, and therefore the thickness of each layer of coating should always be linked to the load and should be guaranteed in order to prevent the frequent appearance of pits.
Rafael Herrera said that relative bitumen still has a lot to study and do, for example, bitumen emulsions, which in other countries are already on the market and even help fix holes with ease and without using high temperatures.
