Introduction of the "gold rule" of the budget in the Constitution
The leadership of the large coalition of social democrats and Christian democrats in Austria decided on Tuesday to write down a budgetary "gold rule" in the constitution to reduce the budget deficit and thus avoid possible downgrading of Austria's state credit rating agencies (triple A).
The Chancellor of Social Democracy, Werner Faymann, personally announced the decision at the end of the meeting of the Council of Ministers, with the Austrian public debt of 74.6 per cent, which is much higher than the 60 per cent ceiling set by the Maastricht Treaty, but below the public debt of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
If Austria's capacity to pay fell by only one point, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay interest by 3,000 million euros more each year, put forward an argument by the Vice Chancellor and the Minister for Foreign Affairs of Christian Democrats Michael Spindelegger.
Austria thus met the demand of the Eurozone summit on 26 October in Brussels; the heads of State and Government demanded a reduction of fiscal deficits by the end of 2012 and a return to balanced public accounts through a constitution or equivalent law.
The regulation adopted by the Austrian Government resembles the "German model", as Germany was the first European country to adopt the "rule".
Until 2017, the structural deficit of the State budget should be reduced by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year, and from 2017, the structural deficit of the federal State budget should not exceed 0.35% of GDP in any year, and land, like communes, should submit balanced budgets.
The goal is to force public debt to fall below the 60 per cent mark of the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/2021.
