Although the German renewable energy model is sometimes cited as an example, reality contradicts this argument.
Berlin ' s choice will result in an increase in the cost of electricity, an increase in energy dependence, compounded by an increased demand for imported gas, particularly from Russia, and a surge in carbon dioxide emissions due to the construction of gas and coal stations.
In a few months, all these unpleasant effects will be felt.
The case of Denmark should be considered.
The European Turbine Champion, from which it receives 30 per cent of its electricity, is also the largest consumer of coal and gas due to intermittent wind, resulting in carbon dioxide emissions and electricity prices being 65 per cent and 50 per cent higher, respectively, than the European average.
On the other hand, thanks to the persistence of our energy policy, our neighbours pay 40 per cent more for electricity than French households.
Since in a globalized economy the price of energy is a key factor in the competitiveness and maintenance of industrial equipment in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity available in Europe.
Consequently, any meaningful reduction in nuclear power will result in a huge increase in the cost of electricity, which will make the beautiful statements about our country ' s new industrialization and the protection of purchasing power an illusion.
The price most French refuse to pay, especially since they do not object to this type of energy in principle.
