Immigration is a burden or good for the economy?
The policy of immigration under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from a variety of points of view - the overloading of police, judicial and administrative services subordinate to the policy of numeracy and its compatibility with France's self-proclaimed status as a "human rights State".
Then there was the administrative harassment of foreign students, which came into the news, when the Minister of the Interior (Liberación of 23 May) said that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and waiters".
But it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
There is much agreement between the right and the left on this issue.
The right tone was set by Jacques Shirac, who in 1976 stated that "900,000 unemployed will not be a problem in a country with 2 million foreign workers", and by the left, Michel Rocar, who explained in 1990 that France "can't accept the poor from all over the world".
The only difference is the level of generosity.
In 2005, fear of invasion by the Polish plumber was felt by both left and right.
Both sides see immigration as a burden on the French economy and on French society.
The only difference is the level of generosity that they intend to show to immigrants.
In his program, François Holland confined himself to platitudes, saying that "joint work will solve our immigration problem".
This perception of immigration as a burden and a problem may give an electoral advantage, but it is economically expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Jeffrey Cameron remind us in a recent book summarizing recent immigration data (Special People: How Migration has shaped our world and will shape our future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among professionals about the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries that receive immigrants.
Restricting immigration reduces growth and reduces employment.
Fear of immigrants ' influence is based on the perception that they can replace local workers, especially the low-skilled, by triggering lower wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than they are replacing local labour by performing jobs that lack local labour.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract local labour and the most skilled work in dynamic sectors where training is not linked to job offers.
Positive impact on wages
Just as it would be difficult for a surgeon to work in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, the complementarity that exists between locals and immigrants results in the arrival of immigrants having a positive impact on the wages of local workers.
Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1 per cent increase in migration flows led to an increase of 0.6-0.9 per cent in real long-term wages.
This goes without the fact that the diversity of immigrants has contributed to the creation of new ideas and economic growth (the United States Nobel Prize winners have a large proportion of naturalized immigrants, and Google, Intel, Paypal and Yahoo have all been based on immigrants).
Migrants also bring net profits to social security systems, giving an average of 1 per cent of the total European budgets.
According to the World Labour Organization, for example, in Germany, an immigrant who arrived at the age of 30 will make a net profit (income minus expenditure) to the State budget in his or her lifetime, on average 150,000 euros.
At the beginning of his mandate, Nicolas Sarkozy was going to "tooth" cling to missing growth points.
The teeth mentioned, which were used to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
