Why is the unemployment rate among disabled workers so high?
Approximately 19 per cent of disabled persons seek employment.
The 15th week of employment for disabled persons begins today.
Despite the policy of public charity launched in 2005, the unemployment rate of persons with disabilities is still twice as high as the average, i.e. 19 per cent as against 9 per cent for the general population.
Disappointing?
"No," says Eric Blanche, Director General of Adapt, an organization that organizes a week of employment for disabled people."
"A great deal of progress has been made in 15 years."
"The unemployment rate was three times higher at the time, not two."
"But there's still a lot of work to do."
It must be said that there are still many barriers to employment for a disabled person.
Of these, 37 per cent are older than 50 years of age (17 per cent on average).
Rather, they have low qualifications: 80 per cent do not have a bachelor ' s degree and only 10,000 out of 2.3 million students in higher education are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment, which is 85 per cent for persons with disabilities, is very common, compared with 38 per cent on average.
In short, these are all criteria that make it very difficult to return to work and that are at the heart of the problem", according to Christian Grapen, Director General Tremplin, an association set up in 1992 to help companies hire a disabled worker.
Here are some of the obstacles.
There is no need to talk about mentalities that are changing, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre Association on behalf of Cité revealed that the managers interviewed had a low level of knowledge of disability and "presumed complete people in wheelchairs or mentally or mentally disabled persons".
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from the goal of having 6 per cent of disabled workers set out in the 1987 law.
The most recent known figures for 2008 are 2.6 per cent.
"We're about 3% today," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefe, the organization responsible for collecting taxes from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: The number of "taxed" organizations, like the amounts paid, decreased from 59,000 to 46,000 in 2007-2011 (and from Euro606 to Euro480 million).
"The 2005 Act, which raised the tax, put a lot of pressure on companies, explains Pierre Blanc."
"But this improvement also reflects an increase in consciousness, particularly in large enterprises."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59 per cent of organizations with between 20 and 49 employees have disabled workers, compared to 82 per cent of organizations with between 100 and 199 employees.
